.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/decisions/deferred_decisions.md:168:## 4. F34: playbook TEST EXECUTION structure deviation
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/decisions/deferred_decisions.md:172:20 scenario files under `manual_testing_playbook/0[5-8]--*/` use a deviating §3 TEST EXECUTION structure (numbered command steps plus `### Expected Signals` plus `### Failure Modes`) instead of the canonical sk-doc subsections (`### Prompt`, `### Commands`, `### Expected`, `### Evidence`, `### Pass / Fail`, `### Failure Triage`).
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/decisions/deferred_decisions.md:176:Each of the 20 files received a documentation note at the top of §3 TEST EXECUTION explaining the deviation is intentional and pointing here for rationale.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/decisions/deferred_decisions.md:183:- Force the runtime checks into a more abstract form, losing the directness that makes operator validation reliable.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/decisions/deferred_decisions.md:185:The deviation is intentional and shipped with the documentation note.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/decisions/deferred_decisions.md:189:None. Status quo. If a future sk-doc template revision broadens the canonical structure to include the current shape, the deviation notes can be removed in a single sweep.
