   256	## 10. `hub_skills`
   257	
   258	**Purpose**: Returns skills with the highest combined in plus out degree across all edge types.
   259	
   260	**Input**:
   261	
   262	```json
   263	{ "queryType": "hub_skills", "topN": 5 }
   264	```
   265	
   266	**Output shape**:
   267	
   268	```json
   269	{
   270	  "queryType": "hub_skills",
   271	  "topN": 5,
   272	  "skills": [
   273	    { "skillId": "system-spec-kit", "inDegree": 18, "outDegree": 6, "total": 24 },
   274	    { "skillId": "sk-doc", "inDegree": 12, "outDegree": 4, "total": 16 },
   275	    { "skillId": "system-skill-advisor", "inDegree": 9, "outDegree": 7, "total": 16 }
   276	  ]
   277	}
   278	```
   279	
   280	**Worked example**: `system-spec-kit` is the highest-degree hub because almost every other skill depends on its validation workflow. Use this query to identify high-blast-radius skills before refactors.
   281	
   282	**Gotcha**: A high degree count does not mean a skill is high-quality. It just means many other skills point at it. Cross-reference with `advisor_validate` accuracy slices to see whether routing TO this skill is actually high-precision.
   283	
   284	---
   285	
   286	## 11. `orphans`
   287	
   288	**Purpose**: Returns skills with zero edges in either direction.
   289	
   290	**Input**:
   291	
   292	```json
   293	{ "queryType": "orphans" }
   294	```
   295	
   296	**Output shape**:
   297	
   298	```json
   299	{
   300	  "queryType": "orphans",
   301	  "skills": []
   302	}
   303	```
   304	
   305	**Worked example**: A healthy skill graph has zero orphans. Every skill should declare at least one outbound or inbound edge so the advisor can route to it via graph signals.
   306	
   307	**Gotcha**: An orphan skill will still surface in `advisor_recommend` if its explicit_author or lexical lanes score high enough. But the graph_causal lane contribution will be zero. Orphans are a signal to add at least one edge in the skill graph-metadata.json.
   308	
   309	---
   310	

