     1	---
     2	title: Manual Testing Playbook Creation - Templates and Standards
     3	description: Templates for creating feature-catalog-style manual testing playbooks with an integrated root playbook, root-level per-feature files, current frontmatter conventions, and orchestration guidance.
     4	---
     5	
     6	# Manual Testing Playbook Creation - Templates and Standards
     7	
     8	Templates for creating manual testing playbooks with deterministic scenarios, structured evidence collection, integrated root-level review/orchestration guidance, root-level per-feature files, and current frontmatter conventions.
     9	
    10	---
    11	
    12	## 1. OVERVIEW
    13	
    14	**Purpose**: Manual testing playbooks provide operator-facing validation matrices for skills. They define deterministic scenarios with realistic user requests, orchestrator execution guidance, exact prompts, command sequences, expected signals, and pass/fail criteria so any operator can execute and grade tests consistently.
    15	
    16	**Key Characteristics**:
    17	- **Deterministic**: Every scenario has an exact prompt and exact command sequence.
    18	- **9-column contract**: Standardized table covering Feature ID through Failure Triage.
    19	- **Feature-catalog rooted**: The root playbook acts as the directory, review surface, and cross-reference index.
    20	- **Per-feature files**: Each scenario gets its own file in a numbered category folder at the playbook root.
    21	- **Orchestrator-led**: Scenarios should mimic real user testing, including coordinator prompts, delegation decisions, and user-visible outcomes.
    22	- **Integrated root guidance**: Review protocol and orchestration rules live inside the root playbook, not in separate canonical sidecar docs.
    23	- **Feature-catalog shaped files**: Per-feature playbook files should mirror feature-catalog snippet structure by leading with prose, then current reality, then structured source references.
    24	- **Evidence-driven**: Every scenario requires captured evidence with explicit verdicts.
    25	- **Validator-limited**: The current validator checks the root playbook for markdown structure, but it does not recurse into category folders or verify cross-file references yet.
    26	- **Evergreen**: Playbooks validate current behavior. Scenario IDs are allowed; spec or phase packet-history references are not.
    27	
    28	**Location Convention**: `{SKILL_PATH}/manual_testing_playbook/`
    29	
    30	Canonical layout:
    31	
    32	```text
    33	manual_testing_playbook/
    34	├── manual_testing_playbook.md          # Root directory page, review rules, and orchestration guidance
    35	├── 01--category-name/                  # Required per-feature files for category 1
    36	│   ├── 001-feature-name.md
    37	│   └── 002-feature-name.md
    38	└── 02--another-category/               # Required per-feature files for category 2
    39	    └── 001-feature-name.md
    40	```
    41	
    42	**Existing Examples**:
    43	- `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/manual_testing_playbook/` (integrated root playbook + 195 per-feature files)
    44	- `.opencode/skills/system-code-graph/manual_testing_playbook/` (older package shape; migrate toward integrated root guidance)
    45	
    46	---
    47	
    48	## 2. WHEN TO CREATE PLAYBOOKS
    49	
    50	**Create a playbook when**:
    51	- A skill has 5+ distinct features that need manual validation.
    52	- Automated tests do not cover integration-level or end-to-end behavior.
    53	- Multiple operators (human or AI) will execute the same test suite.
    54	- Release readiness requires structured evidence collection.
    55	- Realistic orchestration behavior matters, including sub-agent or alternate-CLI usage.
    56	
    57	**Keep simple when**:
    58	- Skill has fewer than 5 features.
    59	- All behavior is covered by automated tests.
    60	- A single operator will run tests once.
    61	
    62	Decision tree:
    63	
    64	```text
    65	Skill has 5+ manually testable features?
    66	  YES -> Does it need structured evidence for release?
    67	    YES -> Create root playbook + root-level per-feature files
    68	    NO  -> Create lightweight checklist in spec folder
    69	  NO -> Document test steps inline in spec folder tasks.md
    70	```
    71	
    72	---
    73	
    74	## 3. CATEGORY AND ID DESIGN
    75	
    76	Each category groups related features under a short prefix.
    77	
    78	| Category Purpose | Example Prefix | Example IDs |
    79	|---|---|---|
    80	| Existing features | `EX` | EX-001, EX-002 |
    81	| New features | `NEW` | NEW-001, NEW-002 |
    82	| Phase features | `PHASE` | PHASE-001, PHASE-002 |
    83	| Memory/spec-kit workflows | `M` | M-001, M-002 |
    84	
    85	ID format:
    86	
    87	```text
    88	{PREFIX}-{NNN}
    89	```
    90	
    91	- `PREFIX`: 1-5 uppercase letters identifying the category.
    92	- `NNN`: zero-padded 3-digit sequence number starting at 001.
    93	- IDs are unique across the entire playbook.
    94	- Gaps are allowed; do not renumber published IDs.
    95	- IDs should identify current validation scenarios, not the packet that created them. Replace packet-history notes with source anchors or feature references.
    96	
    97	Per-feature file path:
    98	
    99	```text
   100	manual_testing_playbook/{CATEGORY_DIR}/{NNN}-{feature-name}.md
   101	```
   102	
   103	Per-feature file shape:
   104	1. `## 1. OVERVIEW`
   105	2. `## 2. SCENARIO CONTRACT`
   106	3. `## 3. TEST EXECUTION`
   107	4. `## 4. SOURCE FILES`
   108	5. `## 5. SOURCE METADATA`
   109	
   110	---
   111	
   112	## 4. THE 9-COLUMN SCENARIO CONTRACT
   113	
   114	Every scenario row uses exactly 9 columns:
   115	
   116	| # | Column | Content |
   117	|---|---|---|
   118	| 1 | Feature ID | `PREFIX-NNN` |
   119	| 2 | Feature Name | Short human-readable name |
   120	| 3 | Scenario Name / Objective | What the scenario proves |
   121	| 4 | Exact Prompt | Copy-paste-ready natural-language prompt |
   122	| 5 | Exact Command Sequence | Deterministic steps with `->` separators |
   123	| 6 | Expected Signals | Observable outputs per step |
   124	| 7 | Evidence | What to capture as proof |
   125	| 8 | Pass/Fail Criteria | Binary grading rule |
   126	| 9 | Failure Triage | Ordered debugging checks |
   127	
   128	Copy-paste header:
   129	
   130	```markdown
   131	| Feature ID | Feature Name | Scenario Name / Objective | Exact Prompt | Exact Command Sequence | Expected Signals | Evidence | Pass/Fail Criteria | Failure Triage |
   132	|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|
   133	```
   134	
   135	---
   136	
   137	## 5. ROOT PLAYBOOK SCAFFOLD
   138	
   139	Copy this scaffold to create `{SKILL_PATH}/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md`:
   140	
   141	```markdown
   142	---
   143	title: "{SKILL_NAME}: Manual Testing Playbook"
   144	description: "Operator-facing reference combining the manual testing directory, integrated review/orchestration guidance, execution expectations, and per-feature validation files for the {SKILL_NAME} skill."
   145	---
   146	
   147	# {SKILL_NAME}: Manual Testing Playbook
   148	
   149	This document combines the full manual-validation contract for the `{SKILL_SLUG}` skill into a single reference. The root playbook acts as the operator directory, review protocol, and orchestration guide: it explains how realistic user-driven tests should be run, how evidence should be captured, how results should be graded, and where each per-feature validation file lives. The per-feature files provide the deeper execution contract for each scenario, including the user request, orchestrator prompt, execution process, source anchors, and validation criteria.
   150	
   151	---
   152	
   153	This playbook package adopts the Feature Catalog split-document pattern for the `{SKILL_SLUG}` skill. The root document acts as the directory, review surface, and orchestration guide, while per-feature execution detail lives in the numbered category folders at the playbook root.
   154	
   155	Canonical package artifacts:
   156	- `manual_testing_playbook.md`
   157	- `{CAT1_DIR}/`
   158	- `{CAT2_DIR}/`
   159	
   160	---
   161	
   162	## 1. OVERVIEW
   163	
   164	This playbook provides {SCENARIO_COUNT} deterministic scenarios across {CATEGORY_COUNT} categories validating the `{SKILL_SLUG}` skill surface. Each feature keeps its original ID and links to a dedicated feature file with the full execution contract.
   165	
   166	Coverage note ({PLAYBOOK_DATE}): {COVERAGE_NOTE}.
   167	
   168	### Realistic Test Model
   169	
   170	1. A realistic user request is given to an orchestrator.
   171	2. The orchestrator decides whether to work locally, delegate to sub-agents, or invoke another CLI/runtime.
   172	3. The operator captures both the execution process and the user-visible outcome.
   173	4. The scenario passes only when the workflow is sound and the returned result would satisfy a real user.
   174	
   175	### What Each Feature File Should Explain
   176	
   177	- The realistic user request that should trigger the behavior
   178	- The orchestrator brief or agent-facing prompt that should drive the test
   179	- The expected execution process, including delegation or external CLI use when relevant
   180	- The desired user-visible outcome
   181	- The implementation or regression-test anchors that justify the scenario
   182	
   183	---
   184	
   185	## 2. GLOBAL PRECONDITIONS
   186	1. Working directory is project root.
   187	2. {PRECONDITION_2}
   188	3. {PRECONDITION_3}
   189	4. {PRECONDITION_4}
   190	5. Destructive scenario {DESTRUCTIVE_IDS} MUST verify recovery is possible.
   191	
   192	---
   193	
   194	## 3. GLOBAL EVIDENCE REQUIREMENTS
   195	- Command transcript
   196	- User request used
   197	- Orchestrator or agent-facing prompt used
   198	- Delegation or runtime-routing notes when applicable
   199	- Output snippets
   200	- Final user-facing response or outcome summary
   201	- Artifact path or output reference
   202	- Scenario verdict with rationale
   203	
   204	---
   205	
   206	## 4. DETERMINISTIC COMMAND NOTATION
   207	- CLI commands shown as `{CLI_TOOL} <subcommand> [args]`.
   208	- MCP tool calls shown as `{MCP_TOOL_PREFIX}({ key: value })`.
   209	- Bash commands shown as `bash: <command>`.
   210	- Agent prompts shown as `agent: <instruction>`.
   211	- `->` separates sequential steps.
   212	
   213	---
   214	
   215	## 5. REVIEW PROTOCOL AND RELEASE READINESS
   216	
   217	### Inputs Required
   218	
   219	1. `manual_testing_playbook.md`
   220	2. Referenced per-feature files under `manual_testing_playbook/NN--category-name/`

